\par\pard\plain \li400\fi360\ri400\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The more general language is probably used so that the concept of God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s omnipotent, creative call can be applied specifically to Abraham\u8217\'92s situation. As the object of Abraham\u8217\'92s faith, God is surely the one who names or speaks \u8220\'93of things in the remotest futurity \u8230\'85, with as much certainty as if they existed\u8221\'94 (DeWelt, 66). When God said to Abraham, \u8220\'93I have made you a father of many nations\u8221\'94 (}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosref/Bible.Ge17.5"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cf3 Gen 17:5}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 ), he spoke of the future, as-yet-unborn legions of believers as though they already existed (MP, 328). Thus Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s faith required him to believe that God controlled the future, and that he could and would bring into existence things which then existed for him only in the form of promises (}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosref/Bible.Heb11.10"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cf3 Heb 11:10}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 , }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosref/Bible.Heb11.13-16"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cf3 13\endash 16}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 ). This is an example for us today, since we also must believe that God can and will one day call into being our not-yet-existing redeemed bodies and their eternal home in the new heavens and new earth.}
