\par\pard\plain \li400\ri400\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The first aspect of Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s faith was that }{\f1\fs24\b1\i0 he gave glory to God.\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8230\'85}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  The \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93glory\u8221\'94 of God is his collective greatness, his total perfection, his manifested majesty (see }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosref/Bible.Ro1.21"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cf3 1:21}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 ). It cannot be increased; it can only be acknowledged and honored. We \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93give\u8221\'94 glory to God by honoring him and by calling attention to everything that makes him great. The very essence of justifying faith is that it gives glory to God, since it is faith }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 in God}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  and in what }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 he}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  has done and promises to do, rather than a reliance upon ourselves and what we are able to achieve. Faith by its very nature puts ourselves in the background and turns the spotlight upon God.}
