\par\pard\plain \li400\ri400\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 This verse sets forth the second aspect of Abraham\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s faith: }{\f1\fs24\b1\i0 being fully persuaded that God had power to do what he had promised}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 . The verb means \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93to be fully persuaded, fully convinced, fully assured.\u8221\'94 Toward what was this total confidence directed? Nothing less than the }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 promises of God}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 . Everything rested on whether or not God could keep his promises; Abraham believed that he could. He believed in the promises because he believed in the power, the \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93wonder-working power\u8221\'94 of God, the power that is able to raise the dead and create from nothing (}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://ref.ly/logosref/Bible.Ro4.17"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cf3 4:17}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 ).}
\par\pard\plain \li400\fi360\ri400\ql\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Stott rightly points out that trusting in a person\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s promises requires believing he has not only the }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 power}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  to keep them, but also the }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1 will}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  to do so. I.e.}
