\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24 Justification means to Paul }{\f0\fs24\i1 God\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s act of remitting the sins of guilty men, and accounting them righteous, freely, by his grace, through faith in Christ, on the ground, not of their own works, but of the representative law-keeping and redemptive blood-shedding of the Lord Jesus Christ on their behalf}{\f0\fs24 . (For the parts of this definition, see Rom. 3:23\endash 26; 4:5\endash 8; 5:18f.) Paul\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s doctrine of justification is his characteristic way of formulating the central gospel truth, that God forgives believing sinners. Theologically, it is the most highly developed expression of this truth in the NT}
